{"cursor":"2838","size":15,"audio":[],"currentlang":"en","article":"{{Infobox Weapon |name= EPK (Pyrkal) Machine gun |image= |caption= EPK\n(Pyrkal) Machine gun |origin= |type=Light machine gun \n|is_ranged=yes  |service= |used_by= Built for the\nHellenic Army |wars=  |designer= Pyrkal staff\n|design_date=1939 |manufacturer=EPK (Pyrkal), Athens |unit_cost=\n|production_date= |number= |variants= \n|weight= (unloaded) |length= |barrel_length=  |cartridge=7.92x36mm EPK |caliber= 7.9 mm |action= gas\noperated |rate= 720 rounds per minute |velocity= |range= |max_range= |feed=\nBox Magazine |sights= Iron }}\n\nThe 'EPK Machine Gun' was designed by EPK, a Greek defense company (in English,\n\"Greek Powder and Cartridge Company\", GPCC) later known as Pyrkal. The gun's\ncreation is connected to EPK's ambitions to become a major producer of infantry\nweapons and a relevant 1937 proposal to the Greek government. The proposal was\nfollowed by the development of a modern machine gun of EPK-own design, as well\nas construction of a small number of prototypes in 1939. The whole project,\nincluding building of infrastructure for massive production of the gun was\nunderway when war with Italy broke out on October 28, 1940, and subsequent\nevents prohibited its completion. A total of no more than (probably) 10-15 was\nbuilt, their fate (except for one given as a present to a member of the Greek\nRoyal Family) remaining unknown. Later publications suggested that this\n7.92Â mm weapon exhibited characteristics at the time closer to those of a\nsubmachine gun; others, though, including Pyrkal itself, have argued that the\nweapon was indeed a very advanced design for its time, featuring pioneering\nelements of a whole class of assault rifle types that appeared later. Its\nconstruction is close to the Thompson submachine gun with ergonomics and weight\nare somewhat compatible with the present day Ultimax 100 light machine gun.\n","linknr":100,"url":"EPK_(Pyrkal)_Machine_gun","recorded":1